reviewText:
This game was a new for me as:
a) I never cried at a video game until this game;
b) I have never played a point and click adventure game until this game;
c) I genuinely cared about some of the characters in this game and what happens to them.
If your looking for a game to really immerse yourself in, and if you don't really care about the gameplay more over the story, then this game is a must have. It's one of the best games I've played in recent memory and deserves all the praise it gets. And if your complaining that you wont enjoy the game because the internet already spoiled the ending for you, your wrong.

// Review - Introduction //

I've been playing PC games long enough to remember the days of the first point-and-click adventure games, and story-driven fmv games with minimal UI.  I enjoyed them for what they were; similar to those interactive novels that once were popular; making a choice and seeing how it affects the story is rewarding. It is with distinct gusto, then, that I herald Telltale Games as the single best developer for this type of genre that I have ever witnessed.  They have single-handedly resurrected and revolutionized the concept of a story-driven game, and I am awed at the compelling drama that is The Walking Dead: Season One.

// Story - Immersion //

This is the number one thing I care about in a story-driven game, as might make sense; Telltale manages to give you meaningful choices; that affect the outcomes of who lives and who dies.  There are many times where you can't prevent a death, however, as the story must go on.  They can't write an outcome for every single possibility, sadly.  But I never found that the linear progression was anything other than...immersive.  Sublime.  Surreal.  I felt like Lee Everett.

// Story - Morality //

People love Mass Effect for it's Paragon/Renegade system, and so do I.  The idea of having the freedom to express your morality, your...discrimination when it comes to morally gray, or lose-lose type of choices, usually with an urgency that rushes you to choose from your gut.   You may find yourself surprised with the option you pick...and you may be disgusted with the final outcome.  Nevertheless, you must push through.  You're either alive, or you aren't.  This effect...gives this game infinite replay value, in my opinion.  Every playthrough can be intuitive, different, like an interactive movie, a virtual reality where you're along for the ride.

// Story - Characters //

I loved them all.  No time to go into details; but they are compelling.  Some of them you love to hate; but the voice acting, the script, the atmopshere, the...pathos, the underlying emotional motives;  it is all spot on.  I have NEVER heard better voice acting, more organic and appopriate to it's theme, than this game.   I imagine some folks might not like the ethnicity of the protagonist, and I can only chuckle heartily at the game they are missing out on.  When the much feared, much anticipated climax was upon me, my eyes watered with true empathy for these fictional people on my screen.  Tears welled up and started to slowly run.   My Lee's show ended with a bang; and a tear fell from my eye as the screen faded to black.  Perfect.

// Interactive Environments //

Gone are the King's Quest days of cumbersome inventories and unwieldly combat; Telltale games mixes their beautiful narrative with heart-attack tense moments of survival stealth, zombie-slaying combat, and the occasional homicidal outburst.

// Microsoft X-Input Controller Support //

This is a big one for me.  If you own an Xbox 360 controller, or any other modern gamepad that supports the X-Input gamepad driver, you can use said gamepad fluidly and flawlessly in this game.  A game like this benefits from a gamepad, as there are many moments of rapidly button mashing 'A' to pry zombies off of you and avoid your entrails being ripped out of you.  A keyboard would probably work OKAY; but it was developed to be played on a gamepad.   Don't believe the hipster fad of dissing gamepads being used with PCs; they have USBs on them for a reason.

// Telltale Games -- Conclusion //

I don't want to seem like a fanboy.  I have absolutely nothing invested emotionally in this company; I didn't know they existed before a very generous friend bought me this game as a gift; but having completed the game, I must say...these people are the real deal.

If you want to support creative, intellectual, immersive, content-rich, story-driven, complex games that cause one to reconsider his very perspective of reality...please...support this company.
